==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /hof/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[hof-]]', from Indo-European ''*keup-'', a suffixed form of ''*keu-'' ‘bend, cove, hollow’.  Cognate with Old Saxon ''hof'' (Dutch ''hof''), Old High German ''hof'' (German ''[[Hof]]'' ‘courtyard’), Old Norse ''hof'' ‘temple’ (Norwegian ''[[hov]]'' ‘hill’).
====Noun====
'''hof''' ''n'' (pl. ''hofu'')

# [[house]]
# [[courtyard]]

===Pronunciation===
/ho:f/
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[hofaz]]'', whence also Old High German ''[[huof]]'', Old Norse ''[[hófr]]''
